    <id>tag:www.gov.uk,2005:DetailedGuide/17335</id>
    <published>2012-12-03T20:59:12+00:00</published>
    <updated>2012-12-03T20:59:12+00:00</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://www.gov.uk/fishing-industry-regulations"/>
    <title>Fishing industry regulations</title>
    <content type="html">&lt;div class="govspeak"&gt;&lt;h2 id="introduction"&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fisheries regulations in England and Wales help maintain a compliant fishing industry in English and Welsh waters. Marine enforcement officers of the Marine Management Organisation (&lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt;) carry out inspections of fishing vessels to monitor compliance with &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and UK fisheries legislation. Inshore fisheries are separately managed by inshore fisheries and conservation authorities (&lt;abbr title="inshore fisheries and conservation authorities"&gt;IFCAs&lt;/abbr&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This guide outlines the procedures you need to be aware of regarding vessel inspections, both in harbour and at sea. It also explains the changes to inshore fisheries management and the powers that IFCA enforcement officers have to tackle illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing on the high seas.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="the-blue-book"&gt;The Blue Book&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Blue Book is a consolidated version of UK and &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; fisheries legislation. The &lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; try to maintain The Blue Book with up-to-date legislation but cannot guarantee that it is up to date at all times.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/fisheries/monitoring/regulations_bluebook.htm"&gt;More information on The Blue Book, including recent amendments and copies to download, on the &lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="what-to-expect-from-a-vessel-inspection-in-harbour"&gt;What to expect from a vessel inspection in harbour&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Marine enforcement officers (&lt;abbr title="marine enforcement officers"&gt;MEOs&lt;/abbr&gt;) carry out inspections of fishing vessels either in harbour or at the time of landing to comply with &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and UK fisheries legislation. Inspections may be conducted at any time of the day or night.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; inspects vessels in a fair, courteous and professional way. During an inspection, &lt;abbr title="marine enforcement officers"&gt;MEOs&lt;/abbr&gt; will:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;identify themselves when meeting you to inspect your vessel&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;only board a vessel when they consider it safe to do so&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;conduct a catch composition inspection on landing including a full box count and/or a check of weighing by species&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;undertake a vehicle inspection if the catch is to be transported to another port&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="what-you-need-to-show-an-inspector"&gt;What you need to show an inspector&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fishing vessel masters are expected to show full fisheries related documentation, catch and fishing gear. An inspector will check:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;documents such as logbook, licence and variations and permits, fishroom plan and Certificate of Registry&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;catch in the fishroom and compare this with the logbook&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;gear on deck, as it must conform to appropriate mesh sizes and dimensions for the fishing area and target species&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;an onshore box count and of weighing methods&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;transport documents which must be carried for transportation of fish&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;landing declaration for hake, cod and sole&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/fisheries/monitoring/documents/code-harbour.pdf"&gt;Download the code of conduct for vessel inspections in harbour from the &lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF 58KB).&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After an inspection, an MEO will advise fishers on fisheries regulations as appropriate. &lt;abbr title="marine enforcement officers"&gt;MEOs&lt;/abbr&gt; should investigate any apparent offences in a fair, impartial and professional manner, and avoid interfering unnecessarily with the landing of catches.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you have a complaint about an inspection, you should contact your local marine area manager:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Head of Marine Compliance&lt;br&gt;
Marine Management Organisation&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Lancaster House&lt;br&gt;
Hampshire Court&lt;br&gt;
Newcastle upon Tyne&lt;br&gt;
NE4 7YH&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Email: &lt;a href="mailto:ops@marinemanagement.org.uk"&gt;ops@marinemanagement.org.uk&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Tel: 0191 376 2642&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="what-to-expect-from-a-vessel-inspection-at-sea"&gt;What to expect from a vessel inspection at sea&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="marine enforcement officers"&gt;MEOs&lt;/abbr&gt; carry out inspections of fishing vessels at sea to comply with &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and UK fisheries legislation. Inspections at sea may happen during the day or night.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; inspects vessels in a fair and professional way and boarding teams aim to conduct inspections quickly so they do not hold up fishing operations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;During an inspection, fishing vessel masters should continue to use marine very high frequency (&lt;abbr title="very high frequency"&gt;VHF&lt;/abbr&gt;) radios and monitor &lt;abbr title="very high frequency"&gt;VHF&lt;/abbr&gt; channel 16 (the international calling and distress signal). They should respond when hailed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Inspectors will usually give notice of an inspection and boarding, unless communication is not possible. Masters of fishing vessels should:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ensure the safe embarkation of boarding teams&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;provide a an appropriate boarding ladder &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;provide a lee as necessary&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="what-you-need-to-show-an-inspector-1"&gt;What you need to show an inspector&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fishing vessel masters are expected to show full fisheries-related documentation, catch and fishing gear. This includes checking:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;documents such as logbook, licence and variations and permits, fishroom plan and Certificate of Registry &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;assessment of catch in fishroom and comparison with logbook and weighing check&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;gear for appropriate mesh sizes and dimensions&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/fisheries/monitoring/documents/code-sea.pdf"&gt;Download the code of conduct for vessel inspections at sea from the &lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF 55KB).&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Any offences will be dealt with in a fair, impartial and professional manner and the MEO will advise fishers on fisheries regulations where appropriate. If you have a complaint about an inspection, you should contact your local district marine officer:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Head of Marine Compliance&lt;br&gt;
Marine Management Organisation&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Lancaster House&lt;br&gt;
Hampshire Court&lt;br&gt;
Newcastle upon Tyne&lt;br&gt;
NE4 7YH&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Email: &lt;a href="mailto:ops@marinemanagement.org.uk"&gt;ops@marinemanagement.org.uk&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Tel: 0191 376 2642&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="inshore-fisheries-management"&gt;Inshore fisheries management&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Under the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009, ten inshore fisheries and conservation authorities (&lt;abbr title="inshore fisheries and conservation authorities"&gt;IFCAs&lt;/abbr&gt;) have replaced sea fisheries committees (&lt;abbr title="sea fisheries committees"&gt;SFCs&lt;/abbr&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Each IFCA manages an IFC district that covers part of the English coast that goes out to six nautical miles and its inland boundaries align with those of its constituent local authorities. &lt;abbr title="inshore fisheries and conservation authorities"&gt;IFCAs&lt;/abbr&gt; also manage sea fisheries resources in estuaries that fall within their districts. &lt;a rel="external" href="http://archive.defra.gov.uk/environment/marine/documents/interim2/ifca-map.pdf"&gt;Download a map of the IFCA districts from the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (&lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt;) website (PDF 589KB).&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="inshore fisheries and conservation authorities"&gt;IFCAs&lt;/abbr&gt; have powers in regards to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;boarding and inspecting vessels&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;entering and inspecting premises, dwellings and vehicles&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;inspecting documents&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="inshore fisheries and conservation authorities"&gt;IFCAs&lt;/abbr&gt; have powers to make byelaws to manage sea fisheries resources within their districts and for wider environmental purposes - eg the protection of species and habitats from fishing activity.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Each IFCA governing committee is made up of:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;one seat each for representatives from the Marine Management Organisation (&lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt;), the Environment Agency and Natural England&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;elected representatives of county and unitary local authorities in the district&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;members who understand the needs and opinions of the local fishing community, and who have knowledge of marine environmental matters&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h2 id="further-information"&gt;Further information&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;h3 id="mmo-helpline"&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Marine Management Organisation"&gt;MMO&lt;/abbr&gt; Helpline&lt;/h3&gt;
